AI-Guided Symbolic Optimization of Noisy Intermediate-Scale Quantum Circuits

Author: Ouadi Maakoul


Abstract

The advent of Noisy Intermediate-Scale Quantum (NISQ) processors offers the potential for quantum advantage, but their utility is severely limited by hardware noise and short coherence times. Circuit depth is directly correlated with error accumulation; thus, minimizing depth is paramount. Current quantum compilers rely on hand-crafted rewrite rules and heuristic search, leaving substantial room for improvement. This dissertation proposes a novel neuro-symbolic framework that leverages large language models (LLMs) to discover new symbolic rewrite rules, automatically verifies their correctness using algebraic and graphical methods, and employs reinforcement learning (RL) to search for optimal transformation sequences under a hardware-aware cost model. By integrating ZX-calculus as a native representation, Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff (BCH) expansions for approximate compression, and detailed device calibration data, the framework aims to outperform state-of-the-art compilers in both depth reduction and actual execution fidelity on real NISQ hardware. The research is structured in three phases, with clear milestones and evaluation benchmarks, and will culminate in an open-source tool for the quantum computing community.

