Chapter 5: Evaluation Plan

This chapter outlines the methodology for evaluating the proposed framework. We describe the benchmarks, baselines, metrics, experimental setup, and ablation studies that will be used to assess its performance.

5.1 Benchmarks

A diverse set of quantum circuits will be used to evaluate the optimizer. These circuits span different application domains, sizes, and structural characteristics.

5.1.1 QASMBench

We select circuits from the QASMBench suite [18] with 5–20 qubits, including:

· Arithmetic circuits: 5-qubit ripple-carry adder, 8-qubit multiplier.
· Quantum Fourier Transform (QFT): QFT on 5, 10, and 15 qubits.
· Grover's algorithm: Oracle-based search for 5 and 10 qubits.

5.1.2 Variational Quantum Eigensolver (VQE) Ansätze

VQE circuits for small molecules, generated using standard UCCSD ansätze:

· H₂: 4 qubits.
· LiH: 6 qubits.
· BeH₂: 8 qubits.

5.1.3 Quantum Approximate Optimization Algorithm (QAOA)

QAOA circuits for MaxCut on random 3-regular graphs:

· 10-node graphs: 10 qubits, with 10–20 QAOA layers.
· 20-node graphs: 20 qubits, with 10 layers.

5.1.4 Randomized Benchmarking Circuits

To test generalization, we generate random circuits:

· Clifford circuits: 5–15 qubits, composed of H, S, CNOT.
· Parameterized circuits: Random sequences of R_x, R_y, R_z and CNOTs.

5.2 Baselines

The proposed optimizer will be compared against the following state-of-the-art compilers:

· Qiskit (optimization_level=3) – the standard IBM compiler.
· TKET (full optimization) – Quantinuum's compiler with advanced passes.
· PyZX (full simplify) – pure ZX-based optimizer.
· VOQC – applicable to Clifford+T circuits.
· OrQstrator – if publicly available; otherwise a simplified implementation using DRL to orchestrate existing passes will be used.
· Agent-Q – for VQE/QAOA tasks, we will compare against circuits generated by Agent-Q (if available) or use reported results from the literature.

5.3 Metrics

5.3.1 Primary Metrics

· Depth reduction: Percentage reduction in circuit depth relative to the baseline.
· CNOT count reduction: Percentage reduction in number of CNOT gates.
· Estimated fidelity: Using a realistic noise simulator (Qiskit Aer with IBM calibration data), we compute the expected success probability (fidelity) of the circuit.
· Actual fidelity: For a subset of circuits, we will execute on IBM Quantum hardware and measure fidelity via randomized benchmarking or direct state tomography.

5.3.2 Secondary Metrics

· Rule discovery rate: Number of novel, verified rewrite rules generated per CEGIS iteration.
· Compilation time: Wall-clock time taken by the optimizer (excluding hardware execution).
· Fidelity Gap (G_F): Defined as
  G_F = \frac{F_{\text{AI}} - F_{\text{baseline}}}{1 - F_{\text{baseline}}},
  where F_{\text{AI}} is the fidelity achieved by our optimizer and F_{\text{baseline}} by the best baseline. This metric measures the fraction of remaining possible improvement captured.

5.4 Experimental Setup

5.4.1 Noise Simulation

Noise simulations will be performed using Qiskit Aer with noise models derived from actual IBM calibration data. For a chosen device (e.g., ibm_brisbane), we will fetch calibration files and construct a NoiseModel that includes:

· Gate error probabilities for each qubit and connection.
· Thermal relaxation (T1, T2) for idle qubits.
· Readout errors.

Each circuit will be simulated with 10,000 shots to obtain the output distribution. Fidelity will be computed as the Hellinger fidelity between the ideal and noisy distributions (or process fidelity via randomized benchmarking where applicable).

5.4.2 Hardware Execution

We will apply for IBM Quantum credits to execute circuits on real devices. Selected circuits from the benchmark set (small to medium size) will be submitted to machines such as ibm_brisbane or ibm_kyiv. Success probability will be measured according to the application (e.g., energy error for VQE, approximation ratio for QAOA, process fidelity for benchmarking circuits).

5.4.3 Statistical Significance

All experiments will be repeated multiple times with different random seeds (for circuit generation or noise simulation). Results will be reported as mean ± standard deviation.

5.5 Ablation Studies

To isolate the contribution of each component, we will perform the following ablation studies:

1. Rule source: Compare performance using only seed rules (from PyZX/VOQC) versus using the full set including LLM-discovered rules. This measures the value of novel rule discovery.
2. Reward components: Evaluate the optimizer with different cost functions:
   · Depth only,
   · Depth + CNOT count,
   · Full hardware-aware cost (including fidelity and SWAP overhead).
     This quantifies the impact of noise-awareness.
3. Search algorithm: Compare MCTS (with policy network) against greedy rule application (always apply the rule with highest immediate cost reduction) and random rule selection. This assesses the benefit of learned search.
4. Global error budget: Run with and without the global error budget for BCH-based approximate rewrites to determine whether error control is necessary for achieving high fidelity.

5.6 Summary

The evaluation plan is designed to rigorously test the proposed framework against existing methods across a range of circuits and metrics. By including ablation studies, we will be able to attribute performance gains to specific components of the system. All results will be reported transparently, and the code and data will be made publicly available to facilitate reproducibility.

Chapter 6: Contributions

This dissertation will make several original contributions to the field of quantum circuit optimization, spanning neuro-symbolic AI, formal verification, and hardware-aware compilation. The contributions are organized into six main areas.

6.1 Neuro-Symbolic Rewrite Rule Discovery

The first major contribution is a novel method for discovering symbolic rewrite rules using large language models (LLMs) guided by Counter-Example Guided Inductive Synthesis (CEGIS). Unlike prior work that relies on hand-crafted rule sets or simple pattern matching, this approach:

· Targets stubborn fragments: By focusing on subcircuits where existing optimizers fail, the LLM is challenged to produce genuinely useful transformations.
· Iteratively expands the rule database: The CEGIS loop ensures that discovered rules are verified and added to a growing library, which can be reused across many circuits.
· Combines creativity with correctness: The LLM proposes candidate rules, but formal verification guarantees equivalence, eliminating the risk of hallucination.

This contribution advances the state of the art by demonstrating that LLMs can be effectively harnessed to augment the symbolic knowledge base of quantum compilation, potentially uncovering optimizations that human experts have missed.

6.2 Formal Verification Framework for Rewrite Rules

To ensure the correctness of discovered rules, we develop a multi-tiered verification framework that integrates:

· Exact symbolic verification for small, non-parameterized rules using matrix algebra in SymPy/QuTiP.
· ZX-calculus based verification for larger or Clifford+T circuits, leveraging PyZX's equivalence checking capabilities.
· Symbolic verification for parameterized rules using computer algebra to handle continuous parameters.

This framework is a contribution in itself, as it provides a practical pipeline for automatically validating arbitrary rewrite rules, which can be used independently of the discovery mechanism.

6.3 ZX-Calculus as a Unifying Representation for AI-Driven Optimization

The dissertation will demonstrate the advantages of using ZX-calculus as the core representation for AI-guided circuit optimization. Key aspects include:

· Graphical structure: The circuit becomes a graph, making local transformations natural and enabling the use of graph neural networks for state representation.
· Native rewrite support: Many standard optimizations are already encoded as ZX rules, providing a rich starting point for the rule database.
· Seamless verification: ZX-calculus offers efficient equivalence checking, which is essential for validating discovered rules and for ensuring that the search engine preserves correctness.

By adopting ZX-calculus, the proposed framework unifies representation, optimization, and verification, offering a clean and powerful foundation for future research.

6.4 Hardware-Aware Search with Reinforcement Learning and MCTS

A core algorithmic contribution is the design of a search engine that combines reinforcement learning and Monte Carlo Tree Search to explore the space of circuit transformations. The search is guided by a hardware-aware cost function that incorporates:

· Circuit depth and CNOT count (primary optimization targets).
· SWAP overhead estimated from the target device's coupling map.
· Estimated fidelity derived from device calibration data (gate errors, T1/T2 times).

The use of action templates based on semantic subcircuit clusters reduces the action space and makes learning feasible. The integration of a GNN policy with MCTS enables the agent to learn effective optimization strategies from self-play, without requiring human demonstrations.

6.5 Approximate Compression via BCH with Global Error Budget

The dissertation will introduce a method for lossy circuit compression using truncated Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff (BCH) expansions. This includes:

· Automatic detection of gate sequences amenable to approximate merging.
· Error bounds for truncated BCH series, ensuring that approximation errors are quantified.
· A global error budget that accumulates approximation errors and prevents them from exceeding a user-defined threshold.

This contribution addresses the practical need to trade off circuit depth for accuracy in the NISQ era, where small approximations may be acceptable if they lead to significant reductions in noise sensitivity. The theoretical analysis of error propagation in this context is novel.

6.6 Dynamic Re-Optimization for Real-Time Hardware Adaptation

Finally, the dissertation will propose a dynamic re-optimization mechanism that decouples the expensive rule-discovery and search from the final hardware-specific tuning. Key elements include:

· Parameterized circuit templates that mark flexible zones (e.g., qubit assignments, SWAP placements).
· Fast micro-optimization that runs immediately before execution, using the latest calibration data to adjust the circuit for minimal error.

This contribution addresses the practical reality that device calibration changes over time, ensuring that optimized circuits remain near-optimal at runtime without incurring the full cost of re-running the search.

6.7 Open-Source Implementation and Benchmarking Suite

As a secondary but important contribution, the dissertation will produce an open-source implementation of the entire framework, including:

· The rule discovery module (LLM + CEGIS loop),
· The verification pipeline,
· The RL/MCTS search engine,
· The hardware adaptation components.

The code will be accompanied by a benchmarking suite that includes the circuits described in Chapter 5, along with scripts to reproduce the evaluation. This will enable other researchers to build upon the work and to compare future optimizers against a common baseline.

