Appendix D: Noise Model Derivations

D.1 Depolarizing Channel

The single-qubit depolarizing channel with error probability p is:

\mathcal{E}_p(\rho) = (1-p)\rho + \frac{p}{3}(X\rho X + Y\rho Y + Z\rho Z).

Its average fidelity with the identity is F = 1-p. For a sequence of L independent depolarizing channels, the overall channel is also depolarizing with effective error probability 1-(1-p)^L, leading to exponential decay.

D.2 Thermal Relaxation (T1/T2)

The amplitude damping channel models energy relaxation:

\mathcal{E}_{T_1}(\rho) = E_0 \rho E_0^\dagger + E_1 \rho E_1^\dagger,

with E_0 = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & \sqrt{1-\gamma}\end{pmatrix}, E_1 = \begin{pmatrix}0 & \sqrt{\gamma} \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}, where \gamma = 1 - e^{-t/T_1}.

The dephasing channel (phase damping) is:

\mathcal{E}_{T_2}(\rho) = E_0 \rho E_0^\dagger + E_2 \rho E_2^\dagger,

with E_0 = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & \sqrt{1-\lambda}\end{pmatrix}, E_2 = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 \\ 0 & \sqrt{\lambda}\end{pmatrix}, where \lambda = 1 - e^{-t/T_2}.

Combined, they give the thermal relaxation channel, which can be expressed as a Pauli channel with probabilities that depend on T_1 and T_2.

D.3 Product Model for Circuit Fidelity

Assuming independent errors, the fidelity of a circuit is the product of fidelities of individual gates. For a gate with error probability p, the fidelity is 1-p. Thus:

F_{\text{circuit}} = \prod_{g \in \text{gates}} (1-p_g).

This is an approximation because errors may not be independent, but it is commonly used in NISQ analysis and serves as a practical cost function.

